	<clause id="_primary_methods_for_the_practical_realization_of_the_definition_of_the_metre" obligation="normative"><title>Primary methods for the practical realization of the definition of the metre</title><p id="_e0405b2c-438a-4352-a144-54dc107f0770">The fundamental equation underlying the above definition of the metre is a direct relationship between a length, a time interval and the speed of light:</p>
	<formula id="equation-1">
	<stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>l</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>c</mi><mo>⋅</mo><mo>Δ</mo><mi>t</mi><mi>,</mi></math></stem>
	</formula>
	<p id="_63b71e2a-05dc-4c54-acd0-a9341c9fd684">in which <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>c</mi></math></stem> is the fixed value for the speed of light in vacuum, <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>c</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>299792458</mn><mo rspace="thickmathspace">⁢</mo><mrow xref="U_NISTu1.u3e-1/1"><mi mathvariant="normal">m</mi><mo rspace="thickmathspace">⁢</mo><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">s</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></mrow>
